collection.description: This collection features our conversations throughout the State of Maine held with educators, students, community members, and major Maine industry professionals. We are asking what youth will need to thrive personally, civically, and economically in the Maine of 2050. The collection is expanding daily, so check back!
collection.title: Maine ED 2050

highlights.description:
#2050youthcontributions 
Re: helping adults understand mental health
It is such a big thing now ever since Covid, so many people have just felt like there voices have been squashed, and don't feel like people care about them.
students are starting to have different values than today's adults, students want to do the things they enjoy not just what earns them money.
It's a hard decision for kids to make, choosing what to do for the rest of their lives. It's a lot of pressure.
I still agree that promoting more of a better idea of post-high school preparations and lifestyle would be very beneficial.

Opening peoples eyes to what is going on in our community is very important if someone can't understand someone then things can go wrong, it will be harder to help and achieve things if you don't understand someone.
This is exactly what we need, more of this, maybe not just with our parents, but teachers, friends, peers, etc...

I think what Maria said here was very striking and true to many people and it can branch into the topic of common standards set by others that can bring someone to believe their dreams aren't "realistic".

For adults to learn how to help students, students have to teach them first. They cant break that stigma and figure out how to help students in need on their own. they would need people from the newer generations to help them learn.

Once again, we cant just expect adults to know how to handle these situations when they were taught how to handle mental health differently. If students want this to change they have to help kick-start that mindset shift.
Listening to the student or offering up input on things like this would be very helpful!

Here I tried to explain how the very one-sided influence of college can create a lot of pressure on kids and the idea that the way to be successful is through college is wrong and can be extremely pressuring on kids.

The older generation is not very reliant on coping strategies. I know I have struggled immensely with my mental health, and with older parents, I was super worried about asking to try different methods because it wasn't openly talked about. I was scared that because I couldn't figure it out on my own that I was giving up or that I was a failure. The conversation needs to be opened up more about different types of healthy coping mechanisms, therapy, medications, etc. Some people need more help than others and that can be hard to understand for people who are not well-educated on the issue.
Again, helping adults who are not very aware of this topic understand what helps, how to get help, and how to help people with mental health struggles would benefit us in the long run.
Helping students prepare for adult life.
We are a very sport school, but we should pay attention to the arts more, they are amazing.
Yes it does matter! This is more important than what people think it would be they are WRONG!
